About
The Pavillons de Bercy-Musée des Arts Forains house one of the largest collections of entertainment and fairground art's objects. They are located in ancient wine warehouses built by a Gustave Eiffel apprentice in the end of the 19th century. Discover the site and its four venues: Théatre du Merveilleux (Thetre of Marvels), Salons Vénitiens (Venetian Rooms), Théâtre de Verdure (Vegetal outdoor area) and the Musée des Arts Forains (Museum àof Fairground Art), all displayed with themes such as Cabinet of curiosities, Venetian carnival, Extraordinary gardens and funfairs of the Belle Epoque (End of the 19th century). This private museum is opende throughout the year, only by apointement in order to experiment the spirit of the place in a lively and participative tour. The guides takes the visitor on an out of time journey, enables them to ride carousels and listen to an automaton show. The Pavillons de Bercy are opened to visit throughout the year only by appointment. And exceptionnally without booking twice a year during the European Heritage Days and Festival du Merveilleux. All the venues can also be rented for private events.
Duration: 1-2 hours

    Magic in the Museum
    This private museum is a repository of century-old fairground and festival artifacts, including cabinets of curiosity, fairground games, carousels, and an automaton opera (precursor to Disney's animatronics!). Visitors can play the games, ride the carousels, dance to the organ (which operates with punched cards passing through a metal mechanism) and appreciate the visually beautiful, evocative setting. Our tour guide (Natalie?) was terrific and though the tour was in French we had English handouts and she spoke some English at times (and other languages for other guests from abroad). The children on the tour were absolutely entranced but so were we adults. Reservations are essential.

  • Hsteinmiller
    Yorktown, Virginia969 contributions
    Release your inner child!
    OMG, this delightful place melted my heart! My inner child was running madly all over the place, although outwardly I remained relatively calm. What a fun, unusual, and fascinating place, full of unique history of the Belle Époque/Gilded Age. Some items on display were over 100 years old and still in working order. We rode on different Merry-go-Rounds, played a horse derby game reminiscent of corn hole, and watched gorgeously dressed automatons perform. The icing on the cake was our guide, Liber, who easily was the most entertaining and enchanting of the three I saw there. Even though the ticket said the tour was French only, he graciously went back and forth from French to English to make sure everyone understood. He was like a big child himself, so enthusiastic about sharing this special place with us, bursting into song and constantly making jokes. It definitely was the highlight of my trip! Make sure you request Liber as your guide, and make your reservation early!

Best regards, The Musée des Arts Forains
